1
00:00:02,120 --> 00:00:05,192
When I've achieved what
I've set out to achieve,

2
00:00:05,280 --> 00:00:07,078
I will let you know
where to find the guns.

3
00:00:07,600 --> 00:00:09,034
So what shall I do?

4
00:00:09,120 --> 00:00:11,839
Get close to him.
Find out where those guns are heading.

5
00:00:14,040 --> 00:00:15,951
Raise your hand,
all those who want to strike!

6
00:00:16,040 --> 00:00:17,553
[ALL CHEERING]

7
00:00:17,640 --> 00:00:20,473
Freddie Thorne is at the
very top of my list.

8
00:00:20,560 --> 00:00:23,791
Well, cross him off.
I'll make him part of our deal.

9
00:00:23,920 --> 00:00:27,311
To hell with them. The more they try
and stop us, the madder I'll be.

10
00:00:27,760 --> 00:00:30,400
In times like these, a communist
in family is bad for business.

11
00:00:30,800 --> 00:00:32,029
You have to leave the city.

12
00:00:34,800 --> 00:00:37,519
TOMMY: <i>You were also at war with
the Lees, Mr. Kimber, am I right?</i>

13
00:00:38,080 --> 00:00:41,072
Together, we can beat them.
Divided, maybe not.

14
00:01:00,440 --> 00:01:01,589
[GIGGLING]

15
00:01:02,520 --> 00:01:04,079
God, he's getting big now!

16
00:01:04,840 --> 00:01:06,433
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

17
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:09,149
Not at all.

18
00:01:12,360 --> 00:01:16,593
<i>♪ Where the viaduct looms
like a bird of doom</i>

19
00:01:16,680 --> 00:01:19,718
<i>♪ As it shifts and cracks</i>

20
00:01:20,760 --> 00:01:24,833
<i>♪ Where secrets lie in the border fires</i>

21
00:01:24,920 --> 00:01:27,070
<i>♪ In the humming wires... ♪</i>

22
00:01:27,160 --> 00:01:30,994
-So, how was London?
-It was crackling with revolution.

23
00:01:31,080 --> 00:01:33,469
The Poplar Docks are on strike.

24
00:01:33,560 --> 00:01:35,631
Did our friends give us
what we asked for?

25
00:01:38,680 --> 00:01:41,274
-How much?
-200 pounds.

26
00:01:41,680 --> 00:01:45,150
-Who did you meet?
-An attaché from the Russian Embassy.

27
00:01:45,480 --> 00:01:47,630
In a Chinese restaurant.
[CHUCKLES]

28
00:01:48,680 --> 00:01:52,150
Our revolution is international.
It grows by the day.

29
00:02:08,280 --> 00:02:10,669
Jeremiah, Jeremiah, what do you see?

30
00:02:11,440 --> 00:02:13,511
Your sister and Freddie
got back this morning.

31
00:02:13,720 --> 00:02:17,953
I tried following them.
But Freddie's so good at getting away.

32
00:02:18,440 --> 00:02:21,159
-He's like a fish.
-Right.

33
00:02:21,240 --> 00:02:22,639
Well, keep fishing, eh?

34
00:02:42,640 --> 00:02:45,678
[SPEAKING FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

35
00:02:48,520 --> 00:02:49,669
MAN 1: Last bets, now.

36
00:02:49,760 --> 00:02:52,080
MAN 2: Now, don't go spending
all your rent money, Charlie.

37
00:02:53,080 --> 00:02:56,357
That's your starters, gentleman.
No more bets.

38
00:02:58,760 --> 00:03:00,194
-I was there on time.
-Finished.

39
00:03:00,840 --> 00:03:03,753
-I've had a tip off. I need this bet.
-The race has started...

40
00:03:03,840 --> 00:03:05,353
-Please.
-[SHOUTING] No!

41
00:03:05,440 --> 00:03:09,638
-Ugh. Fine.
-Get rid of him. I said no.

42
00:03:09,920 --> 00:03:13,231
-Now get out.
-All right, all right, I'm off. I'm off.

43
00:03:29,280 --> 00:03:31,954
-All right, lads. See you tomorrow.
-Cheers.

44
00:03:50,360 --> 00:03:51,475
[DOOR SHUTS]

45
00:03:52,600 --> 00:03:54,318
-It's a good day.
-Where's John?

46
00:03:54,720 --> 00:03:56,552
-John's in The Garrison.
-[SIGHS]

47
00:03:56,640 --> 00:03:58,711
Says he wants a meeting
about a family matter.

48
00:04:00,520 --> 00:04:03,797
After he's said his piece, he'll come
back and take his place with Scudboat.

49
00:04:04,560 --> 00:04:07,074
Scudboat, John will be
here in ten minutes.

50
00:04:07,160 --> 00:04:09,071
-All right.
-Five.

51
00:04:37,840 --> 00:04:39,194
We're here.

52
00:04:47,160 --> 00:04:48,309
Good boy.

53
00:04:58,960 --> 00:05:01,110
[COINS CLINKING]

54
00:05:06,480 --> 00:05:08,039
John?

55
00:05:17,240 --> 00:05:18,799
[ALL YELLING]

56
00:05:18,880 --> 00:05:19,880
Put that down!

57
00:05:22,120 --> 00:05:23,235
This is for Cheltenham.

58
00:05:24,320 --> 00:05:26,436
We just taking back what's ours.

59
00:05:27,120 --> 00:05:29,555
There's loot in here, search everywhere!

60
00:05:36,160 --> 00:05:39,630
All right, John. There's only one... Not
now. Only one man guarding the house.

61
00:05:40,960 --> 00:05:43,679
-What's troubling you?
-[CLEARS THROAT]

62
00:05:44,440 --> 00:05:48,195
Polly, you know what it's been like
since Martha died.

63
00:05:48,280 --> 00:05:50,237
God takes the best first.

64
00:05:50,320 --> 00:05:54,712
The truth is, my kids have been
running bloody rings around me.

65
00:05:55,640 --> 00:05:58,632
Running barefoot with the
dogs until all hours.

66
00:06:00,400 --> 00:06:02,656
Pol, give him ten bob for
some new shoes. Is that it, John?

67
00:06:02,680 --> 00:06:04,637
Tommy, we'd be better
to do this without you.

68
00:06:07,440 --> 00:06:08,589
Now, what's your point?

69
00:06:10,640 --> 00:06:13,109
What the kids need is a mother.

70
00:06:16,320 --> 00:06:17,879
So that's why I'm getting married.

71
00:06:19,720 --> 00:06:22,720
POLLY: Does this poor girl know you're
gonna marry her or are you just gonna

72
00:06:22,760 --> 00:06:24,717
spring it on her all of the sudden?

73
00:06:25,200 --> 00:06:26,429
I've already proposed.

74
00:06:26,560 --> 00:06:27,959
And she said yes.

75
00:06:28,360 --> 00:06:31,830
I think there's a shell about
to land and go bang.

76
00:06:35,400 --> 00:06:38,119
It's, um, it's Lizzie Stark.

77
00:06:38,200 --> 00:06:40,157
[CHUCKLING]

78
00:06:42,680 --> 00:06:45,194
John! Lizzie Stark's a strong woman,

79
00:06:45,320 --> 00:06:47,880
and I'm sure she provides
a fine service for her customers.

80
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:49,911
I won't hear the word.

81
00:06:50,640 --> 00:06:53,075
Understand? Do not use that word.

82
00:06:53,600 --> 00:06:55,591
What word is that, John?

83
00:06:56,200 --> 00:06:59,511
-You know what word that is.
-Everybody bloody knows.

84
00:06:59,600 --> 00:07:01,159
Everybody can go to hell.

85
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:05,311
Whore? That word.
Or prostitute? How about that one?

86
00:07:06,240 --> 00:07:11,269
All right, I want it known,
if anyone calls her a whore again,

87
00:07:11,360 --> 00:07:14,876
I will push the barrel of my
revolver down their throats,

88
00:07:14,960 --> 00:07:17,270
and blow the word back
down into their hearts.

89
00:07:17,360 --> 00:07:20,318
Men and their cocks never
cease to amaze me.

90
00:07:21,040 --> 00:07:24,112
John, Lizzie Stark never did
a day's work vertical.

91
00:07:24,200 --> 00:07:27,158
She's changed. All right, people change.

92
00:07:27,240 --> 00:07:29,516
Like with religion.

93
00:07:29,600 --> 00:07:31,796
Oh, Lizzie Stark's got religion, eh?

94
00:07:32,560 --> 00:07:34,471
No, no, she doesn't
have religion, but...

95
00:07:35,680 --> 00:07:37,114
Well, she loves me.

96
00:07:38,080 --> 00:07:42,039
Now, listen, Tommy. I won't do it
without your blessing.

97
00:07:43,800 --> 00:07:49,352
But of all the people in the world,
I want you to see it...

98
00:07:50,880 --> 00:07:53,394
-As brave.
-Oh, it's brave, all right.

99
00:07:53,480 --> 00:07:56,393
POLLY: Brave is going where no
man has gone before.

100
00:07:57,520 --> 00:08:00,592
And with Lizzie Stark, John, that is
really not what you'll be doing.

101
00:08:00,680 --> 00:08:01,715
Give me some time.

102
00:08:01,840 --> 00:08:03,353
Welcome her to the family

103
00:08:04,120 --> 00:08:06,270
as someone who's had a hard life.

104
00:08:07,760 --> 00:08:09,990
All right, because I need someone.

105
00:08:11,800 --> 00:08:13,438
All right, the kids need someone.

106
00:08:13,920 --> 00:08:16,833
[DOOR OPENS]
Tommy, we've been done over.

107
00:08:17,120 --> 00:08:18,155
What?

108
00:08:23,680 --> 00:08:25,193
Jesus Christ!

109
00:08:25,560 --> 00:08:27,312
What the bloody hell happened here?

110
00:08:27,920 --> 00:08:32,391
The Lees, all of them. Cousins, nephews.

111
00:08:32,800 --> 00:08:34,279
Even the bastards.

112
00:08:34,880 --> 00:08:37,161
POLLY: They've taken anything
they can lay their hands on.

113
00:08:39,840 --> 00:08:41,194
Four cash boxes.

114
00:08:43,160 --> 00:08:45,436
-They left these.
-Wire cutters?

115
00:08:46,040 --> 00:08:48,429
-Why would they leave wire cutters?
-Nobody move.

116
00:08:51,200 --> 00:08:52,918
I think our friends
are playing the game.

117
00:08:53,440 --> 00:08:57,399
-What game?
-Pol, don't, don't touch anything.

118
00:08:59,360 --> 00:09:00,998
Erasmus Lee was in France.

119
00:09:02,080 --> 00:09:03,195
Shit.

120
00:09:07,920 --> 00:09:10,150
When we gave up ground to the Germans,

121
00:09:11,520 --> 00:09:14,911
we'd leave behind booby traps
set up with wires.

122
00:09:16,160 --> 00:09:17,673
Then we'd leave wire cutters.

123
00:09:18,360 --> 00:09:19,395
It's part of the joke.

124
00:09:20,720 --> 00:09:22,677
Somewhere in here
there's a hand grenade.

125
00:09:22,840 --> 00:09:24,160
Holy Jesus.

126
00:09:26,040 --> 00:09:27,951
Attached to a wire.

127
00:09:29,920 --> 00:09:31,513
Don't move any chairs.

128
00:09:32,560 --> 00:09:34,358
Or open any doors.

129
00:09:37,720 --> 00:09:39,791
Go easy, John boy, easy.

130
00:09:40,080 --> 00:09:41,080
Ah!

131
00:09:41,440 --> 00:09:43,636
Boys, no, there's nothing here.

132
00:09:45,480 --> 00:09:47,630
If it was in here, it would
have blown by now.

133
00:09:48,400 --> 00:09:51,870
It was my name on
that bullet Erasmus sent.

134
00:09:52,960 --> 00:09:54,678
He set up a trap all right.

135
00:09:57,880 --> 00:09:59,279
He set it up just for me.

136
00:10:13,200 --> 00:10:14,395
Finn?

137
00:10:15,880 --> 00:10:17,791
Finn, stay exactly where you are.

138
00:10:18,960 --> 00:10:21,076
[GIGGLES] I was pretending I was you.

139
00:10:23,880 --> 00:10:25,951
Which door did you
open to come in, Finn?

140
00:10:26,040 --> 00:10:27,997
I didn't, I climbed in.

141
00:10:29,880 --> 00:10:34,477
I want you to climb out exactly the
same way you climbed in, okay?

142
00:10:35,880 --> 00:10:37,678
-No, no, Finn!
-[CLATTERING]

143
00:10:39,600 --> 00:10:41,557
-Grenade!
-[ALL YELLING]

144
00:10:45,600 --> 00:10:47,238
[BREATHING HEAVILY]

145
00:11:03,800 --> 00:11:06,758
That's why you should
never pretend to be me.

146
00:11:07,440 --> 00:11:09,317
Okay? Okay?

147
00:11:29,720 --> 00:11:30,755
[WHISTLES]

148
00:11:46,280 --> 00:11:48,476
I got you ten minutes with her.

149
00:11:50,960 --> 00:11:53,918
You can at least say thank you.
It's easier to see the Pope, these days.

150
00:12:02,520 --> 00:12:03,590
[KNOCKING]

151
00:12:19,760 --> 00:12:20,955
[SIGHS]

152
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:27,434
Put your hand on the Bible.

153
00:12:28,200 --> 00:12:29,200
I don't believe.

154
00:12:31,200 --> 00:12:32,873
Anyway, I didn't come here to lie.

155
00:12:34,520 --> 00:12:36,238
This war is cutting us all up.

156
00:12:37,520 --> 00:12:40,990
[SPEAKING ROMANIAN]

157
00:12:44,240 --> 00:12:47,153
-You're all children.
-I say enough.

158
00:12:47,960 --> 00:12:50,873
Your boys tried to kill me. Didn't work.

159
00:12:55,080 --> 00:12:57,959
[SPEAKING ROMANIAN]

160
00:13:06,280 --> 00:13:08,351
No wonder you won't touch a Bible.

161
00:13:08,760 --> 00:13:11,115
-I have ambitions.
-You want to play a switch.

162
00:13:12,320 --> 00:13:14,197
-I need your boys.
-For what?

163
00:13:14,520 --> 00:13:17,990
Kimber's not the brains,
there's a Gadza who runs the races.

164
00:13:18,880 --> 00:13:22,350
I'm collecting smart people,
but I need strong men, too.

165
00:13:23,000 --> 00:13:24,718
Now, your boys should know this.

166
00:13:25,920 --> 00:13:30,278
We now get the winner in one of three
races before the race even starts.

167
00:13:30,520 --> 00:13:33,592
No need for chalkers or rafflers,
I'm talking certainties.

168
00:13:33,680 --> 00:13:36,399
You come in here, boasting you're
gonna do someone down,

169
00:13:36,480 --> 00:13:38,471
and in the same breath,
ask me to trust you?

170
00:13:41,520 --> 00:13:44,273
On my mother's side, we are kin.

171
00:13:46,840 --> 00:13:50,196
[SPEAKING ROMANIAN]

172
00:13:59,640 --> 00:14:01,313
Ada, can you do my back?

173
00:14:04,480 --> 00:14:05,629
Ada!

174
00:14:07,360 --> 00:14:09,192
I know what was in the envelope.

175
00:14:10,560 --> 00:14:12,392
I looked. Money.

176
00:14:12,840 --> 00:14:16,310
And that bloke that we met in London,
who you said was a Frenchman,

177
00:14:16,400 --> 00:14:18,277
he was Russian.
I'm not an idiot, Freddie.

178
00:14:18,720 --> 00:14:21,189
How is it, that you take all the risks

179
00:14:21,280 --> 00:14:23,715
and Stanley Chapman gets the money?

180
00:14:23,920 --> 00:14:25,957
-It's money for the cause.
-[SCOFFS]

181
00:14:26,440 --> 00:14:27,669
You're blind.

182
00:14:28,080 --> 00:14:30,216
I would be, if your brothers
had anything to do with it.

183
00:14:30,240 --> 00:14:33,949
This isn't about them,
this is about you. And me.

184
00:14:34,240 --> 00:14:36,436
And this.

185
00:14:39,400 --> 00:14:41,994
[SIGHS] You're a dreamer, Freddie.

186
00:14:43,160 --> 00:14:46,039
You give money away
while we rot in here.

187
00:14:47,600 --> 00:14:49,637
You talk about revolution.

188
00:14:50,720 --> 00:14:51,835
I need to know.

189
00:14:56,040 --> 00:14:58,156
Who are you loyal to, Freddie?

190
00:15:01,360 --> 00:15:03,237
I said, who are you loyal to?

191
00:15:03,720 --> 00:15:04,835
[SIGHS]

192
00:15:22,840 --> 00:15:23,955
[DOOR OPENS]

193
00:15:31,880 --> 00:15:33,439
[DOOR LOCKS]

194
00:15:42,720 --> 00:15:44,518
Did you have something to do with this?

195
00:15:46,360 --> 00:15:48,237
I asked an acquaintance for an address.

196
00:15:48,960 --> 00:15:51,076
She said she'd only give
it to me anonymously.

197
00:15:51,760 --> 00:15:53,353
She's afraid of the consequences.

198
00:15:55,360 --> 00:15:56,509
Whose address is it?

199
00:15:57,720 --> 00:15:59,870
Tommy, I'd like to suggest a strategy.

200
00:16:20,880 --> 00:16:24,157
Your message said
you have an address for me?

201
00:16:28,960 --> 00:16:30,758
Anonymous tip off.

202
00:16:31,880 --> 00:16:34,076
The address of Stanley Chapman.

203
00:16:35,680 --> 00:16:39,355
-You promised me Freddie Thorne.
-This is instead of Freddie Thorne.

204
00:16:40,440 --> 00:16:42,272
-No deal.
-Inspector,

205
00:16:42,840 --> 00:16:45,832
Stanley Chapman is a bigger
fish than Freddie Thorne.

206
00:16:48,560 --> 00:16:51,200
He's currently holding £200 in cash

207
00:16:52,080 --> 00:16:55,550
given to The Communist Party
by the Russian government.

208
00:16:57,240 --> 00:17:00,710
That's right, Chapman
has snow on his boots.

209
00:17:01,120 --> 00:17:03,157
And all you need is a shovel.

210
00:17:04,000 --> 00:17:06,310
If he talks, you'll have proof.

211
00:17:07,880 --> 00:17:09,518
You might even get that medal.

212
00:17:11,200 --> 00:17:12,429
Now,

213
00:17:13,760 --> 00:17:15,671
before I give you the address,

214
00:17:16,840 --> 00:17:18,160
I want your word

215
00:17:19,760 --> 00:17:21,433
that you'll let Freddie Thorne

216
00:17:21,880 --> 00:17:24,269
and my sister leave the city.

217
00:17:27,920 --> 00:17:30,116
Very well. You have my word.

218
00:17:35,760 --> 00:17:37,256
I'd say our little truce
has proven quite

219
00:17:37,280 --> 00:17:39,840
productive for both of us, Inspector.

220
00:17:41,640 --> 00:17:45,190
I'll get the information and protection.

221
00:17:46,160 --> 00:17:49,357
And you? Well...

222
00:17:50,960 --> 00:17:52,439
You get Bolsheviks.

223
00:17:57,320 --> 00:17:59,072
But on a more pressing matter,

224
00:18:01,680 --> 00:18:05,833
I'm afraid that Mr. Churchill
is becoming impatient.

225
00:18:07,320 --> 00:18:08,799
And I fear that,

226
00:18:10,720 --> 00:18:13,553
if you don't get back
those stolen weapons soon,

227
00:18:14,480 --> 00:18:15,834
I will be replaced.

228
00:18:16,480 --> 00:18:18,471
That will be the finish
for me, that's for sure.

229
00:18:19,200 --> 00:18:21,476
When my business with Kimber is done,

230
00:18:21,800 --> 00:18:23,950
the guns will be returned.
That was the deal.

231
00:18:24,040 --> 00:18:26,634
Then I'm in your hands, completely.

232
00:18:28,560 --> 00:18:30,198
You hold all the cards.

233
00:18:31,560 --> 00:18:35,440
But, I hope to God that
my dismissal doesn't come

234
00:18:35,520 --> 00:18:38,751
before your decision to
hand back those guns.

235
00:18:39,400 --> 00:18:41,471
And I say this for your sake because,

236
00:18:43,080 --> 00:18:46,550
if I were to be fired,
and it were your fault,

237
00:18:49,080 --> 00:18:51,310
I would do things that
would shame the devil.

238
00:18:52,320 --> 00:18:53,355
[CHUCKLES]

239
00:18:53,920 --> 00:18:56,355
My fury is a thing to behold.

240
00:18:58,200 --> 00:19:00,669
On my last day in power, for example,

241
00:19:01,680 --> 00:19:02,954
I would see to it

242
00:19:04,040 --> 00:19:07,874
that you and your scum brothers have
your heads stoved in with mallets

243
00:19:08,160 --> 00:19:09,309
and spades.

244
00:19:11,520 --> 00:19:12,999
And your sister, too.

245
00:19:14,200 --> 00:19:17,397
That baby inside her would
be of no consequence to me.

246
00:19:18,440 --> 00:19:20,590
The only one to be spared

247
00:19:21,640 --> 00:19:23,597
would be your little brother Finn.

248
00:19:24,360 --> 00:19:27,830
He would, however, be lifted,
as a juvenile,

249
00:19:28,760 --> 00:19:31,559
and dumped in that part
of the adult prison

250
00:19:32,680 --> 00:19:36,560
where men have the most
appetite for boys like him.

251
00:19:38,200 --> 00:19:41,636
Oh, that would be
a dark day indeed, Mr. Shelby,

252
00:19:43,000 --> 00:19:46,152
if my dismissal comes
before your decision.

253
00:19:47,360 --> 00:19:48,509
You understand?

254
00:19:51,040 --> 00:19:52,519
And know this,

255
00:19:55,000 --> 00:19:56,673
the clock is ticking.

256
00:20:26,280 --> 00:20:27,350
[SNIFFS]

257
00:20:29,800 --> 00:20:31,313
[FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING]

258
00:20:43,000 --> 00:20:44,593
[GRUNTING]

259
00:20:45,520 --> 00:20:47,318
[INDISTINCT SHOUTING]

260
00:20:51,560 --> 00:20:55,030
[MORE SHOUTING]

261
00:20:57,480 --> 00:20:58,834
[YELLING IN PAIN]

262
00:21:03,880 --> 00:21:05,518
Look what we found.

263
00:21:07,160 --> 00:21:09,913
Seems Stanley Chapman really
does have snow on his boots.

264
00:21:12,920 --> 00:21:15,594
Come on. Here we go.

265
00:21:19,640 --> 00:21:21,119
Mr. Chapman...

266
00:21:22,760 --> 00:21:24,239
You're fucked.

267
00:21:35,320 --> 00:21:36,320
[DOOR OPENS]

268
00:21:38,840 --> 00:21:42,356
He still refuses to say
where it came from.

269
00:21:44,520 --> 00:21:46,431
I'm sure with a little persuasion

270
00:21:47,240 --> 00:21:48,878
he'll tell us everything he knows.

271
00:21:50,080 --> 00:21:53,118
Including the whereabouts
of Freddie Thorne.

272
00:21:54,000 --> 00:21:56,640
-Sir?
-Your face is a picture.

273
00:21:57,440 --> 00:21:58,874
But I thought you'd done a deal.

274
00:21:59,680 --> 00:22:02,479
-Oh, is that what you thought?
-Well, you gave your word.

275
00:22:04,080 --> 00:22:05,957
My word.

276
00:22:08,720 --> 00:22:12,190
People still talk about such
things in this idiotic century.

277
00:22:12,440 --> 00:22:15,000
My word to who?

278
00:22:16,160 --> 00:22:17,719
To a Peaky Blinder?

279
00:22:19,440 --> 00:22:23,229
Now, go on and interrogate
Mr. Chapman until he tells

280
00:22:23,320 --> 00:22:26,119
us where we can find
Freddie Thorne and his wife.

281
00:22:27,400 --> 00:22:29,755
The source of the money
is of secondary importance.

282
00:22:32,680 --> 00:22:35,832
You think my campaign against
Shelby has become personal?

283
00:22:37,160 --> 00:22:38,160
Correct.

284
00:22:38,760 --> 00:22:41,434
Spot on, as they say in London society.

285
00:22:42,680 --> 00:22:45,832
Now, go and interrogate Mr. Chapman.

286
00:22:47,160 --> 00:22:49,674
And do not make the mistake
of being too gentle.

287
00:22:51,480 --> 00:22:52,675
Right, sir.

288
00:23:24,760 --> 00:23:25,909
Today's her birthday.

289
00:23:28,960 --> 00:23:30,189
I know you never miss it.

290
00:23:31,280 --> 00:23:32,953
Then I'm lucky you're not a copper.

291
00:23:33,920 --> 00:23:36,150
-What do you want?
-Came to warn you.

292
00:23:38,360 --> 00:23:39,714
They've lifted Stanley Chapman.

293
00:23:40,760 --> 00:23:43,513
How do you know?
Police don't spill that information.

294
00:23:43,800 --> 00:23:45,920
I know because it was me and Tommy
who tipped him off.

295
00:23:46,440 --> 00:23:48,636
Tommy did a deal.
In return for safe passage

296
00:23:48,800 --> 00:23:50,960
for you and Ada,
he's given them Stanley and the money.

297
00:23:51,760 --> 00:23:52,989
Money? What money?

298
00:23:56,920 --> 00:23:59,036
-Who told you about the money?
-Who do you think?

299
00:24:01,360 --> 00:24:02,873
Yeah, it was Ada's idea.

300
00:24:03,560 --> 00:24:06,640
That's how desperate she is to get out
of that rat hole you're keeping her in.

301
00:24:09,720 --> 00:24:12,720
She didn't mind if you knew, just didn't
want to be here when you found out.

302
00:24:13,120 --> 00:24:15,953
Sometimes women have to take over.
Like in the war.

303
00:24:16,040 --> 00:24:17,896
Who the hell do you think you are?
You fucking Shelbys!

304
00:24:17,920 --> 00:24:19,558
Don't you swear over
your mother's grave.

305
00:24:22,640 --> 00:24:25,080
You play your tune, you expect
the whole world to dance to it.

306
00:24:25,160 --> 00:24:26,719
You don't have time for this, Freddie.

307
00:24:28,200 --> 00:24:29,713
You did a deal for me.

308
00:24:30,160 --> 00:24:32,470
Don't flatter yourself. For Ada.

309
00:24:32,560 --> 00:24:34,392
And you think this copper
will keep his word?

310
00:24:35,600 --> 00:24:38,558
If he does, you're safe.
If he doesn't, Chapman will give you up.

311
00:24:38,840 --> 00:24:40,717
You'll still have to leave
town, same result.

312
00:24:42,680 --> 00:24:44,398
-So neat.
-So leave.

313
00:24:44,760 --> 00:24:46,600
Except there's one thing that
you've got wrong,

314
00:24:47,320 --> 00:24:50,438
Stanley won't be able to give up my
address because he doesn't know it.

315
00:24:51,360 --> 00:24:54,830
That's how it works.
None of us know each other's addresses.

316
00:24:56,120 --> 00:24:58,350
So you've wasted your fucking time.

317
00:24:59,920 --> 00:25:03,595
And they'll keep beating him and beating
him for information he doesn't have.

318
00:25:03,880 --> 00:25:07,350
So all you've done is sign the
death warrant of a good man.

319
00:25:09,560 --> 00:25:12,439
-So you won't leave?
-No, I won't fucking leave.

320
00:25:13,160 --> 00:25:16,755
And if you want me out of Birmingham,
it'll have to be in a wooden box.

321
00:25:22,360 --> 00:25:25,318
You lay a hand on our Ada and I'll
put you in a wooden box myself.

322
00:25:36,360 --> 00:25:38,795
You raised a stubborn one there, Irene.

323
00:26:06,560 --> 00:26:08,312
You told me to carry on.

324
00:26:08,400 --> 00:26:09,993
I wanted to stop.

325
00:26:10,600 --> 00:26:12,637
He had some kind of seizure.

326
00:26:16,840 --> 00:26:18,990
[SIGHS] So you killed him.

327
00:26:21,480 --> 00:26:22,629
Did he give you an address?

328
00:26:24,000 --> 00:26:26,719
What's the matter with you?
He fell down some stairs.

329
00:26:26,800 --> 00:26:28,916
This is not bloody Belfast.

330
00:26:29,120 --> 00:26:32,590
Not yet, but if men like him
get their way, it soon will be.

331
00:26:32,800 --> 00:26:37,397
So find some stairs, throw him
down, and call the coroner.

332
00:26:39,240 --> 00:26:40,355
Use Grayson.

333
00:26:41,360 --> 00:26:42,998
If he has any awkward questions,

334
00:26:43,160 --> 00:26:45,959
ask about the welfare of his mistress
in Saltley.

335
00:26:47,040 --> 00:26:48,599
That'll shut him up.

336
00:26:54,320 --> 00:26:56,789
To think I used to live
in a shithole like this.

337
00:26:57,400 --> 00:26:58,834
Bloody animals.

338
00:26:58,920 --> 00:27:01,719
The Shelbys really are doing
an excellent job for us.

339
00:27:03,280 --> 00:27:04,600
We haven't lost a single penny to

340
00:27:04,640 --> 00:27:06,870
rafflers or chalkers
in eight race meetings.

341
00:27:07,480 --> 00:27:08,675
The bookies are purring.

342
00:27:08,920 --> 00:27:10,957
So we throw the dog a bone.

343
00:27:12,200 --> 00:27:13,200
I think so.

344
00:27:19,600 --> 00:27:23,070
Mr. Kimber, Mr Roberts,
come and have a look around.

345
00:27:30,920 --> 00:27:31,990
After you.

346
00:27:32,120 --> 00:27:35,476
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

347
00:27:41,240 --> 00:27:43,151
Well, I thought the Lees
turned you over?

348
00:27:43,240 --> 00:27:45,629
You shouldn't listen to gossip,
Mr. Kimber. This way.

349
00:27:48,760 --> 00:27:50,034
Business is good.

350
00:27:51,280 --> 00:27:52,839
Especially since now you know

351
00:27:52,920 --> 00:27:55,116
which horse is going to win
before you set the odds.

352
00:27:55,560 --> 00:27:57,949
Information is very much appreciated.

353
00:28:00,320 --> 00:28:02,231
All right, well, where are they?

354
00:28:03,200 --> 00:28:05,760
John, Lovelock. Scudboat, in here.

355
00:28:11,000 --> 00:28:12,320
This is my team.

356
00:28:13,000 --> 00:28:15,514
They will take up their pitch at your
convenience, Mr. Kimber.

357
00:28:16,840 --> 00:28:20,037
John is the book, Scudboat is the
bag man, and of course,

358
00:28:20,280 --> 00:28:21,918
we bring our own protection.

359
00:28:24,440 --> 00:28:29,116
Warwick, next Saturday,
at least 50 yards from the beer tent.

360
00:28:55,560 --> 00:28:59,030
Gentleman, and lady.

361
00:29:00,880 --> 00:29:02,473
I have in my hand

362
00:29:02,880 --> 00:29:07,033
a legal betting license,
issued by the Board of Control.

363
00:29:08,600 --> 00:29:12,958
The Shelby family has its first, legal

364
00:29:13,480 --> 00:29:14,709
racetrack pitch.

365
00:29:14,880 --> 00:29:16,791
[ALL CHEERING]

366
00:29:24,640 --> 00:29:25,710
Congratulations.

367
00:29:26,080 --> 00:29:27,150
There you go.

368
00:29:28,680 --> 00:29:29,829
Congratulations.

369
00:29:30,480 --> 00:29:33,154
30, 40, 50...

370
00:29:40,680 --> 00:29:42,717
These cigarettes
have a strange smell, Arthur.

371
00:29:43,480 --> 00:29:45,869
They smell like rotting water.

372
00:29:46,160 --> 00:29:47,195
And look,

373
00:29:47,280 --> 00:29:48,714
rats have got into some of them.

374
00:29:50,400 --> 00:29:51,536
They're stolen, are they not?

375
00:29:51,560 --> 00:29:52,630
Don't ask.

376
00:29:53,560 --> 00:29:55,136
They smell because you
keep them in the boat.

377
00:29:55,160 --> 00:29:58,596
What do you care? Now, can you
come check my adding up, please?

378
00:30:04,200 --> 00:30:06,476
You know, you should make a
new start of this place.

379
00:30:06,960 --> 00:30:08,030
Do it properly.

380
00:30:08,440 --> 00:30:10,158
These cigarettes are not fit to sell.

381
00:30:10,760 --> 00:30:11,909
Smells like Gallipoli.

382
00:30:12,040 --> 00:30:14,316
You should find a new
place to store them.

383
00:30:14,440 --> 00:30:16,670
It has to be far away from coppers.

384
00:30:16,840 --> 00:30:18,160
Oh, but not rats.

385
00:30:18,280 --> 00:30:20,476
All the wharves have rats, Grace.

386
00:30:22,320 --> 00:30:23,913
What's wrong with a dry warehouse?

387
00:30:24,200 --> 00:30:25,315
Tommy's orders.

388
00:30:27,440 --> 00:30:28,555
What orders?

389
00:30:28,960 --> 00:30:32,271
Always keep contraband near
petrol boat moorings.

390
00:30:32,880 --> 00:30:34,200
Don't boats get searched?

391
00:30:34,280 --> 00:30:35,873
We moor them at junctions.

392
00:30:37,280 --> 00:30:38,839
So there's more than one way out.

393
00:30:39,240 --> 00:30:42,039
No locks within a mile
so we can move that stuff,

394
00:30:42,520 --> 00:30:43,590
fast.

395
00:30:44,200 --> 00:30:46,240
Your brother doesn't obey the law,
but he has rules.

396
00:30:46,480 --> 00:30:48,039
Precise man, your brother.

397
00:30:49,160 --> 00:30:50,355
Is my adding up right?

398
00:30:50,480 --> 00:30:51,595
It is now.

399
00:30:54,240 --> 00:30:55,310
CAMPBELL: One.

400
00:30:55,720 --> 00:30:56,790
Two.

401
00:30:57,040 --> 00:30:58,075
Three.

402
00:30:58,560 --> 00:31:00,073
<i>And four.</i>

403
00:31:00,520 --> 00:31:02,796
<i>And we'll search them one-by-one.</i>

404
00:31:09,240 --> 00:31:13,438
Please, Lord, let that which
I seek be found here.

405
00:31:29,120 --> 00:31:31,236
Not so much as a bullet, sir.

406
00:31:31,360 --> 00:31:33,192
Just more cigarettes and whisky.

407
00:31:43,560 --> 00:31:45,551
Arthur tells me you've
been asking questions.

408
00:31:47,520 --> 00:31:48,999
About how we run our business

409
00:31:50,080 --> 00:31:51,400
and how we get our booze

410
00:31:51,720 --> 00:31:52,720
and where we keep it.

411
00:31:53,000 --> 00:31:54,274
I'm just trying to help.

412
00:31:57,440 --> 00:31:58,794
Let's you and me go for a walk.

413
00:32:00,360 --> 00:32:01,475
Where to?

414
00:32:01,560 --> 00:32:02,709
Come on.

415
00:32:12,200 --> 00:32:13,315
Why here?

416
00:32:16,000 --> 00:32:17,991
You're a good Catholic girl, aren't you?

417
00:32:20,280 --> 00:32:21,280
Yes.

418
00:32:21,760 --> 00:32:24,229
Well, then you know it's here
people come to confess.

419
00:32:25,560 --> 00:32:27,153
[SIGHS] After you.

420
00:32:38,800 --> 00:32:40,154
Well, here it is, Grace.

421
00:32:42,280 --> 00:32:43,395
I'll confess.

422
00:32:45,640 --> 00:32:46,710
I need someone.

423
00:32:49,160 --> 00:32:51,754
Kimber has an adviser by
the name of Roberts.

424
00:32:51,960 --> 00:32:53,234
He talks well.

425
00:32:53,640 --> 00:32:55,119
Keeps the accounts.

426
00:32:55,760 --> 00:32:57,637
Runs the legal side of the business.

427
00:32:58,960 --> 00:33:00,075
And you need a Roberts?

428
00:33:01,680 --> 00:33:03,159
Arthur tells me you have ideas.

429
00:33:03,960 --> 00:33:05,553
I'm not an accountant, nor a lawyer.

430
00:33:05,640 --> 00:33:06,710
No.

431
00:33:07,760 --> 00:33:09,478
No, but you have something I need.

432
00:33:10,880 --> 00:33:11,950
Class.

433
00:33:14,080 --> 00:33:16,435
I need someone who looks
right at the big meetings.

434
00:33:16,920 --> 00:33:18,354
Epsom, Ascot.

435
00:33:18,440 --> 00:33:19,760
Is this a job interview?

436
00:33:19,840 --> 00:33:21,320
Arthur says you're good with numbers.

437
00:33:21,400 --> 00:33:24,392
[LAUGHS] Oh, well, that's relative.
He's quite poor.

438
00:33:24,480 --> 00:33:25,480
[SCOFFS]

439
00:33:25,800 --> 00:33:27,234
You keep the books in order.

440
00:33:27,320 --> 00:33:28,549
They were chaotic.

441
00:33:29,560 --> 00:33:30,880
But you're a liar.

442
00:33:36,800 --> 00:33:38,552
No Catholic girl would enter a church

443
00:33:38,640 --> 00:33:40,392
and forget to make
the sign of the cross.

444
00:33:42,960 --> 00:33:43,995
You're very perceptive.

445
00:33:44,080 --> 00:33:46,913
First, you lied to me about that
pub you used to work in.

446
00:33:47,640 --> 00:33:49,551
Now I find out you're a Protestant.

447
00:33:52,640 --> 00:33:54,392
-Do you care?
-No.

448
00:33:55,320 --> 00:33:56,719
I like to fit in.

449
00:33:58,120 --> 00:33:59,315
You pull a pint

450
00:33:59,640 --> 00:34:01,120
like someone who's thinking about it.

451
00:34:01,200 --> 00:34:03,136
This is not an interview,
this is an interrogation.

452
00:34:03,160 --> 00:34:04,160
Sit down.

453
00:34:10,800 --> 00:34:11,915
Look, Grace.

454
00:34:12,760 --> 00:34:13,795
[SIGHS]

455
00:34:13,880 --> 00:34:15,640
You've washed up in a
place you don't belong,

456
00:34:16,440 --> 00:34:17,440
for whatever reason.

457
00:34:19,120 --> 00:34:20,349
My good fortune.

458
00:34:20,480 --> 00:34:21,709
And perhaps mine.

459
00:34:28,120 --> 00:34:29,918
You know that most of
what I do is illegal?

460
00:34:30,720 --> 00:34:31,835
I'm not blind.

461
00:34:32,560 --> 00:34:34,437
And yet you'd still be
willing to work for me?

462
00:34:37,400 --> 00:34:38,959
Are you offering me the job?

463
00:34:39,760 --> 00:34:40,760
[SCOFFS]

464
00:34:43,560 --> 00:34:44,560
Then I accept.

465
00:34:46,560 --> 00:34:48,120
There's something else you should know.

466
00:34:50,160 --> 00:34:53,073
A very important detail about
my reasons for employing you.

467
00:35:14,120 --> 00:35:15,394
You disappoint me.

468
00:35:19,120 --> 00:35:20,349
Do you resign?

469
00:35:22,920 --> 00:35:23,920
No.

470
00:35:25,080 --> 00:35:27,196
My appetite for the work
has only increased.

471
00:35:32,200 --> 00:35:33,200
[CLEARS THROAT]

472
00:35:34,160 --> 00:35:35,360
Tomorrow I'll show you around.

473
00:35:48,640 --> 00:35:49,755
Lizzie!

474
00:35:50,720 --> 00:35:52,199
Hello, Lizzie?

475
00:35:53,480 --> 00:35:55,596
That bag looks heavy. Jump in!

476
00:35:55,760 --> 00:35:57,080
It is.

477
00:35:57,240 --> 00:35:58,435
You like kids?

478
00:35:59,040 --> 00:36:00,599
-Yeah.
-Good,

479
00:36:00,720 --> 00:36:02,074
because John's got four of them.

480
00:36:03,920 --> 00:36:06,480
It's all right, I'm not going
to try to talk you out of it.

481
00:36:23,640 --> 00:36:24,755
I just want to talk.

482
00:36:25,680 --> 00:36:26,680
Then you're against us?

483
00:36:27,680 --> 00:36:29,159
John is his own man.

484
00:36:30,400 --> 00:36:31,515
And you're your own woman.

485
00:36:35,960 --> 00:36:36,960
Now, Lizzie,

486
00:36:37,920 --> 00:36:41,231
since I came back from France,
I've come to you on many occasions.

487
00:36:43,080 --> 00:36:44,593
Tommy, you didn't tell him?

488
00:36:45,080 --> 00:36:46,354
No, I didn't tell him.

489
00:36:47,520 --> 00:36:49,193
Just like you didn't tell him.

490
00:36:50,680 --> 00:36:52,160
Now, why didn't you tell him, Lizzie?

491
00:36:53,200 --> 00:36:54,520
Why didn't you tell him

492
00:36:55,120 --> 00:36:57,919
that you've been serving
his brother for the past two years?

493
00:36:59,640 --> 00:37:00,994
Because the past is the past.

494
00:37:03,120 --> 00:37:04,918
I don't want to lose him.
He's a good man.

495
00:37:06,520 --> 00:37:09,672
That was the answer I was hoping
you'd give. The past is the past.

496
00:37:10,200 --> 00:37:12,111
You see, our John says you've changed.

497
00:37:12,280 --> 00:37:14,635
And I believe him, and that's good.

498
00:37:15,200 --> 00:37:16,349
Change is good.

499
00:37:18,480 --> 00:37:20,198
These are new times I'm told.

500
00:37:24,200 --> 00:37:26,032
So I wish you both every happiness.

501
00:37:27,400 --> 00:37:31,951
And I want you to see that as
my wedding gift to you

502
00:37:33,480 --> 00:37:34,800
and our farewell

503
00:37:34,880 --> 00:37:36,075
to pleasures gone by.

504
00:37:49,240 --> 00:37:50,240
You mean...

505
00:37:51,480 --> 00:37:52,629
One last time?

506
00:37:55,000 --> 00:37:56,070
One last time.

507
00:37:56,480 --> 00:37:57,480
You and me.

508
00:38:00,560 --> 00:38:01,675
It's eight bloody pounds.

509
00:38:04,400 --> 00:38:05,400
[SCOFFS]

510
00:38:22,200 --> 00:38:23,200
So where should we go?

511
00:38:26,840 --> 00:38:28,353
Tommy, should we go to my lodging?

512
00:38:32,280 --> 00:38:34,112
So the past is not the past.

513
